#INSTALLATION

@node inst "Installation made EASY"

/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\
''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''
             Installation of Cybergames
,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/



There are two different installation scripts for
Cybergames. The scripts were written to be used with
the Commodore installer program.


ANYONE should be able to install Cybergames even if
he doesn't know much about his computer.
I went through the tiresome process of learning the
LISP lookalike code to write those scripts and
writing something that actually would work.
It's not perfect, but it's working and it's very easy
to use...


Cybergames can be installed on either three diskettes
or on hard-disk. The game needs to be installed before
it can be run since it uses some Commodore files and
must be properly assigned if on hard-disk.

If you are using a computer with Workbench 1.2 or 1.3
(I think), Cybergames will need

ram-handler
ramdrive.device

The disk-installed Cybergames on WB 1.2 and 1.3 will
need

run
runback
endcli.

If you are using WB 2.04 or higher, you won't need
any of the above, except runback if you are going
to install the game on disk when you don't have
much memory.

Actually runback is used so that I can close the
cli/shell window from which Cybergames is loaded
and started. This way some amount of memory is spared
for you poor dudes who still is sitting with 1 meg
machines. Cybergames will of course work without
beeing started with runback if you have enough memory,
that is. If you don't have runback you can always
change it to 'run' in the Cybergames1:s/startup-sequence
with any simple texteditor.



Here's a complete explanation of what the installement
scripts will do:

For disk
--------

-Formats four empty disks and names them:
 Cybergames1 Cybergames2 Cybergames3 and
 Cybergames_savedisk

-Makes an install on Cybergames1 so that you can
 boot from that diskette.

-Copies all files and dirs from cg1 to the disk named
 Cybergames1

-Copies all files from cg2 to the disk named Cybergames2

-Copies all files from cg3 to the disk named Cybergames3

(On machines with WB 1.2 and WB 1.3)

-Looks for run, runback and endcli in your sys:c
 directory and copies them to the c directory on the
 disk named Cybergames1

-Looks for ramdrive.device in your sys:devs directory
 and copies it to the devs directory on the disk
 named Cybergames1

-Looks for ram-handler in your sys:l directory and
 copies it to the l directory on the disk named
 Cybergames1


(On machines with WB 2.04 or higher)

-Looks for runback in your sys:c directory and copies
 if to the c directory on the disk named Cybergames1




For Hard-disk
-------------

-Copies all files from cg1 cg2 and cg2 to one directory
 on your hard-disk.

-Configurates your startup-sequence with four assigns
 to the new location on the hard-disk.


